{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472529","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472529"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:59:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:59:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1545"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1545","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1545"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.25,0.06,0.18,0.45]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1545"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38529"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1545","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1545"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1545"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22954"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"818"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2427"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3739"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3833"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41663"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42337"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43085"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44051"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38529","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/38529"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 4-year-old boy is brought to the Emergency Department by his mother because of a 3-hour history of chest pain and mild shortness of breath. Immediately prior to this, he was unsupervised in his playroom. He has been well recently, but the mother reports several trips to the hospital for asthma flare-ups.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his blood pressure is 128/86 mmHg, pulse 160/min, temperature 37.5\u00b0C, respiratory rate 38/min and SpO2 90% on room air. There is reduced chest wall motion on the left and subcostal retractions. Auscultation reveals decreased air entry on the left. Percussion note is dull throughout the left side. A chest X-ray is ordered (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is shown on the chest X-ray?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Diaphragmatic hernia","Left haemothorax","Left pneumothorax","Left lung consolidation","Left lung collapse"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe chest X-ray shows a whiteout of the left lung with no clear air bronchograms and a shift of the midline structures to the left side. The trachea can be seen deviated to the left and the right border of the mediastinum has moved across to the midline. This is consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Elung collapse\u003C/strong\u003E (total lung atelectasis) with negative pressure pulling the midline structures towards the affected side.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInterestingly, children are more likely than adults to develop total lung atelectasis. This is because their underdeveloped lungs lack collateral ventilation which becomes apparent during development. Namely, their lungs do not have pores of Kohn and canals of Lambert, which facilitate collateral ventilation of blocked alveoli. As such, following an obstruction, the airway is more likely to collapse. Additionally, infants and young children have a more compliant chest wall which provides less outward force (chest expansion) to oppose the elastic recoil of the lung making them more prone to collapse (i.e., partial complete atelectasis).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe four major types of atelectasis in children are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EObstructive: Most common, due to complete or partial obstruction or large airways. Obstruction occurs due to pathology either intraluminally or intrinsic to the airway wall, or extramural. This type of obstruction is typically caused by a foreign body, mucus plugging, or tumors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EResorptive: Typically results from an alveolar space-filling lesion, like pneumonia. Most commonly seen in patients with neuromuscular disorders (i.e., reduced ability to inflate a lung after a collapse.)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERelaxation: Occurs when contact between the parietal and visceral pleurae is disrupted by a an effusion or pneumothorax.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECompression: Caused by large space-occupying masses within the chest (cysts, cardiomegaly, and/or overinflated lobes that compress adjacent lung segments).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther options:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn a \u003Cstrong\u003Ediaphragmatic hernia\u003C/strong\u003E (uncommon in this age group) the gastric bubble or even bowel loops can be seen in the chest.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemothorax\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Econsolidation\u003C/strong\u003E would result in a midline shift towards the non-affected side (ie. to the right in this case). This is also seen with pleural effusion, diaphragmatic rupture, and/or hernias.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumothorax\u003C/strong\u003E would appear black with no visible lung markings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["White-out of a hemithorax on the chest X-ray has a limited number of causes. The key finding in diagnosis relates to the position of the trachea."],"references":["Iwama I, Kohama M. Unilateral Lung Whiteout in Children. Pediatric Emergency Care 2019;35(1):e1\u20135.","Finder, J., Atelectasis in children [Internet] Uptodae.com 2021 [cited 14 Sep 2021]. Available from \u003Chttps://www.uptodate.com/contents/atelectasis-in-children\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22954"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1545"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"13278"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"13278","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/13278"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/543725e5-802b-4193-b1f8-c7cb5db5d64f.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/543725e5-802b-4193-b1f8-c7cb5db5d64f.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":627,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22954","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/22954"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-07-31T10:50:48+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-19T08:56:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1545"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38529"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.